reviewText:
The film opens with the usual impossible rescue scene. This time it is to rescue Wesley Snipes who will be known as Dr. Death. To his dismay they did so because they needed a fifth for a mission, one that fails. Stallone must go after Mel Gibson, who is not dead, really, but decides to retire his team because he fears for their life. Kelsey Grammer helps him recruit a new team, one that is more akin to an MIB force which includes Kellen Lutz, Ronda Rousey, and Victor Ortiz. Things go their formulaic way and the old guys plus the very talkative Antonio Banderas join the picture...again.

Harrison Ford flew a helicopter like Hans Solo, Jet Li had a minor role that we can see expanding, and of course Arnold is back.

The film is lengthy and spends time to quickly develop all the new players. The banter was not as good as the previous films, but was still acceptable. Banderas' character has "Peter Sellers" potential as a screw up who seems to luck into things.

What best came out of this film was the potential for the next one.

Parental Guide: 1-2 F-bombs. No sex or nudity.

There is just one problem with Expendables 3: if you take away the scenes with bam-boom action, what's left is stale-sounding jokes and expressions of mild psychopathy. The plot, as far as it exists, involves former CIA men headed by Mel Gibson, fighting against Sylvester Stallone's current CIA group, which includes Harrison Ford, Arnold Schwarzenegger, Dolph Dulgren. No wonder, then, that the film's real story is about age and for how long one can excel as a mercenary soldier. Given that a group of people in their 20s and 30s in the film is ultimately replaced by those in the sexagenarian and septuagenarian brackets, the only truly expendables are the young. 2 3/4 stars

After the success of the sequel, everyone knew the Expendables was destine to become a trilogy, because after all, there were still a few action stars who hadn't gotten in on the action (pardon the pun). This time however things did get a little out of hand, as one can see by the enormous cast in the movies poster. the Expendables added something this time around that the other two films were severely lacking in, comedy, whether it was intentional or not. Included in this were how Barney's team had to be bigger than ever to fight the baddest guy of them all, Mel Gibson. Harrison Ford and Arnold Schwarzenegger taking part in a machine gun battle from a golf cart, since they obviously can't run anymore, and they even managed to sneak in a joke about Wesley Snipes being in prison for not paying his taxes. New editions included Kellan Lutz, Kelsey Grammer, Ronda Rousey, and various other UFC personalities, leading to a lot more hand to hand stuff than in previous films, but much like the other films, the third installment of the Expendables was an action junkies dream come true. There were non-stop explosions, gun battles, and bodies, all surrounded by a very thin and improbable story. We don't watch these movies for the story or even the characters, we watch these films simply for the adrenaline rush. In that context alone, Expendables 3 hits the target every time, but if you're looking for a good story, great performances, or even a reason behind the madness, then you're watching the wrong series. When it comes to the Expendables think less Die Hard and more Michael Bay.

And if you've seen a Terminator movie you know how tough Schwarzenegger is.  And even in real life Rhonda Rousey could be the bouncer she portrayed.  So why not believe that together, these stars could whip an army of well trained soldiers, avoid C-4 explosions, survive a tank attack, and after all that, Banderis falls in love, and no one gets a scratch.  Yeah, I can see that.

I was expecting alot more after the first two. It was nice to see the old actions star again and they had some great lines in the movie that called back to their previous roles, but that's about the best I can say really. The effects looked rather pitiful in comparison to other movies, the explosions looked very fake and computer animated in many cases. And perhaps the biggest problem is that the older well known stars all had to take a backseat most of the movie for a newer younger cast of people that I really cared nothing for. Even the Antonio Banderas couldn't have saved this movie as his character seemed very out of place considering the action movies he's been in before. The introduction of him, Mel Gibson, and Wesley Snipes felt like limited, and Gibson's and Snipes' characters were great for the time they had. Overall, it was interesting and the lines from the old standby's were great, but it was definitely lacking.

Almost as if it was a foreign object. Cut to the next scene where he is lying on the floor, settling in as if it were absolutely normal. The scene was small and insignificant to the greater story...if you were only trying to tell an action story. But if you want a story with substance and characters with depth to them, this is how you do that.
